			<h4>Background</h4>
			<p style="text-align:justify">
				<!--<img src="background.png" HEIGHT=48/> <br>-->
				My research at Vanderbilt focussed on solving optimization problems 
in Model Driven Engineering(MDE). The main focus of MDE is to use models
 at all stages of development. MDE has been used to develop software in 
different domains like automotive, avionics, digital signal processing, 
etc. Certain classes of optimization problems are common across 
different domains. For example resource allocation, configuration 
problems frequently occur in telecommunications, avionics domains. 
Existing approaches of solving these optimization problems in MDE 
involve writing problem and domain specific algorithms. This results in a
 solution that is time intensive to develop, requires domain expertise 
and lacks reusability. The objective of my PhD was to create a generic 
framework for modeling and solving optimization problems at model level.
 A domain-engineer with minimal knowledge of constraint-programming can 
create a graphical model of his optimization problem and solve his 
problem. In the backend the framework supports generic translators to 
reduce the problem to a mathematical model that can then be used in 
combination of stochastic search algorithms or given to off-the-shelf 
constraint solvers. 
			</p>
